Setting aside years of animosity, the U.S. government joined with private

humanitarian groups Friday to funnel medicine, tents, clothing, food and other relief materials to help earthquake-stricken Iran.
The quake, which rocked the northern region of Iran early Thursday, left nearly 29,000 dead, by official count, and about 400,000 homeless.
The death toll is expected to rise, however, as rescuers continue work.
"Iran needs assistance, and such organizations are welcome to send it."
As an example, he said "no formalities" will be required for relief planes flying into Iran.
Meanwhile, other U.S. groups were rushing to supply Iran with emergency goods.
